 =20

In negotiations, it is often helpful to have someone else, some =E2=80=9Cab=
sent principal,=E2=80=9D to blame for your position. You go to a car dealer=
ship, the salesperson says =E2=80=9Cthis car costs $25,000,=E2=80=9D you sa=
y =E2=80=9CI want to pay $21,000,=E2=80=9D she says =E2=80=9CI like you, I =
want you in this car, but my boss won=E2=80=99t let me go lower than $24,00=
0,=E2=80=9D you say =E2=80=9C$22,000,=E2=80=9D she says =E2=80=9CI really w=
ant this to work out, let me check with my boss,=E2=80=9D she goes into the=
 break room and watches TikToks on her phone for five minutes, she comes ba=
ck and says =E2=80=9Cmy boss is really mad at me but I talked him down to=
=C2=A0$23,500.=E2=80=9D
The boss is a crutch, an excuse. The salesperson
=09is adversarial to you =E2=80=94=C2=A0she wants to charge more, you want =
to pay less =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=09wants you to=C2=A0feel=C2=A0like she=E2=80=
=99s on your side, so you trust her and agree to her proposals.

The way to solve the tension=C2=A0is to set up some imaginary absent princi=
pal and offload all the adversarial feelings onto him. =E2=80=9CI=C2=A0don=
=E2=80=99t want to charge you this much,=E2=80=9D the salesperson=C2=A0says=
 or implies, =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s just my awful boss; really, you and I ar=
e in this together, both trying to get this deal past him.=E2=80=9D And so =
you pay more than you wanted to, because you like her and feel like she=E2=
=80=99s on your side, and because she has done all she can; she can=E2=80=
=99t get the price any lower; that=E2=80=99s her boss=E2=80=99s fault.
This technique is pretty shopworn at the car dealership, and people have ki=
nd of=C2=A0stopped believing it, but there are better versions. There are, =
in the world, a lot of people who are what the financial industry would cal=
l =E2=80=9Cbroker-dealers=E2=80=9D:=C2=A0Sometimes=C2=A0they act as brokers=
, finding buyers and sellers and negotiating a deal between them as pure ag=
ents, but but other times they act as dealers, owning stuff for their own a=
ccount and buying or selling it=C2=A0at whatever price they can get. Someti=
mes they really do have some absent principal; other times, they are just t=
rading for their own book.
It can be helpful, for these people, to create confusion about which role t=
hey are playing. For instance if you own some stuff and you want to sell it=
 for $100, and your customer says =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll pay $80,=E2=80=9D i=
t can be nice, for you, to say =E2=80=9Chang on, let me see if the seller i=
s willing to go down to $95.=E2=80=9D And then you put the customer on hold=
 and watch TikToks, and=C2=A0you=C2=A0come back and say =E2=80=9CI just tal=
ked to the seller, she=E2=80=99s not happy and yelled at me a lot, but I wa=
s able to talk her down to $96, but that=E2=80=99s the lowest she can go.=
=E2=80=9D And the customer appreciates your good service and your=C2=A0effo=
rts on his behalf, and feels like you and he are in this together, and agre=
es to pay $96. But there was no seller, or rather, you were the seller, and=
 you just didn=E2=80=99t want to go below $96. =E2=80=9CThe seller=E2=80=9D=
 on the other line was just a crutch, an excuse. But the customer doesn=E2=
=80=99t know that; he thinks that you were negotiating on his behalf, tryin=
g to get him the best possible deal. He doesn=E2=80=99t know that you were =
on the other side, and that you were in fact trying to get him the worst po=
ssible deal that he=E2=80=99d agree to.
In the financial industry this is somewhere between =E2=80=9Cfrowned upon=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ca crime that you can go to prison for.=E2=80=9D For =
a while, there was a wave of prosecutions of bond traders who did this stuf=
f; some were acquitted and some convicted, but some of the convictions were=
 reversed and this behavior is, I don=E2=80=99t know, somewhat ambiguously =
illegal. (Obviously not legal advice!) For instance, we=C2=A0once talked ab=
out a US Securities and Exchange Commission case against some Nomura trader=
s who allegedly=C2=A0did stuff like this
  [1]
:
On March 18, 2011, Peters learned that Nomura had purchased a block of the =
bond JPMMT 2006-A3 2A1 at 71-08. Shortly thereafter, Peters contacted a rep=
resentative of a Nomura customer (=E2=80=9CCustomer E=E2=80=9D) and falsely=
 claimed that the bond was being offered at 75-24, implying that a third-pa=
rty, and not Nomura, owned the bond. Peters then elaborated on the misrepre=
sentation, saying that the =E2=80=9Cseller=E2=80=9D (who did not exist) pro=
bably had =E2=80=9Ca little room=E2=80=9D (meaning, to lower the price) but=
 that the bond=E2=80=99s price likely would not fall by more than a point. =
The Customer E representative directed Peters to =E2=80=9CFOK=E2=80=9D (sho=
rt for =E2=80=9Cfill or kill,=E2=80=9D which is industry jargon for =E2=80=
=9Clast and final offer=E2=80=9D) at 74-24, to which Peters replied, =E2=80=
=9CFOK worked!=E2=80=9D By misleading the Customer E representative about t=
he fictional [offer] from the phantom seller, Peters extracted over $117,00=
0 in additional profits for Nomura.
Customer E there thinks that Peters is doing a good job on his behalf, advi=
sing the customer on negotiating=C2=A0with the seller and talking the selle=
r down to the lowest possible price. But in fact Peters is doing a good job=
 on his=C2=A0own=C2=A0behalf, getting the customer to pay the highest possi=
ble price (to Peters) by=C2=A0pretending=C2=A0there is some absent seller o=
n the other side.
This trade was for somewhat thinly traded residential mortgage-backed secur=
ities, by the way, which is important.=C2=A0One reason that this trick does=
n=E2=80=99t work that well anymore at car dealerships, and that it doesn=E2=
=80=99t work at all in=C2=A0the stock market, is that you need a customer w=
ho has no idea what the underlying thing is actually worth. You can=E2=80=
=99t go around pretending to negotiate the price of a share of Apple Inc. s=
tock, because the customer can just look on a screen and see its price, acc=
urate to the penny and the second. You=C2=A0could go around pretending to n=
egotiate the price of a Honda, but the internet has made=C2=A0car prices mo=
re transparent than they used to be. Little stubs of weird RMBS trade by ap=
pointment, and Nomura plausibly does have a much better idea what they cost=
 than its customers do, so it can push up the price by doing a weird little=
 pantomime negotiation.
Meanwhile in the art market prices are more or less entirely imaginary; a G=
ustav Klimt painting is worth, to a billionaire art collector, roughly $1 m=
ore than one other billionaire is willing to pay for it. So if you just mak=
e up a guy who thinks it=E2=80=99s worth $185 million, maybe you can get yo=
ur real billionaire customer to pay that much. The  New York Times reports:

For example, in 2012, Bouvier told Rybolovlev=E2=80=99s aide that the selle=
rs of a Klimt, =E2=80=9CWater Serpents II,=E2=80=9D were looking for $190 m=
illion, but that he thought he could =E2=80=9Ctwist them to get 185,=E2=80=
=9D according to court papers.
=E2=80=9CThese negotiations did not happen,=E2=80=9D Judge Furman wrote in =
his March opinion.
On the same day in 2012 that Bouvier wrote that email, one of his companies=
 bought the painting for $126 million. Two days later, he invoiced Rybolovl=
ev for $183.8 million.

Bouvier is Yves Bouvier, an art broker-dealer, and Rybolovlev is Dmitry Ryb=
olovlev, =E2=80=9Ca Russian oligarch=E2=80=9D and collector. Bouvier would =
sometimes buy art for his own account and then sell it to=C2=A0Rybolovlev a=
t markups of tens of millions of dollars, which is a good trade if he=E2=80=
=99s a dealer and bad work if he=E2=80=99s a broker. The dispute is about w=
hich he was:

For years, Rybolovlev has accused Bouvier of defrauding him in that and doz=
ens of other transactions by posing as an art adviser negotiating sales on =
Rybolovlev=E2=80=99s behalf, when, in fact, he was secretly acting as an ar=
t dealer and often increasing the prices by tens of millions of dollars. =
=E2=80=A6
Bouvier has long insisted he was always clear that he was operating not sol=
ely as an adviser, but also as an independent dealer. As evidence, he has p=
ut forward sales contracts for Rybolovlev=E2=80=99s first few purchases as =
proof he was openly operating as a dealer, free to charge whatever price Ry=
bolovlev was prepared to pay.
But the Russian collector has said that Bouvier=E2=80=99s role evolved into=
 that of commissioned adviser and agent, and that Bouvier pretended to play=
 that role. He has emails in which Bouvier described negotiations with sell=
ers that do not appear to have actually taken place.

We have talked about this case  before, over the years; Rybolovlev has been=
 pursuing Bouvier =E2=80=9Cin jurisdictions that included Monaco, Singapore=
, Hong Kong and Geneva,=E2=80=9D but has mostly lost. This week in New York=
 there will be a trial on=C2=A0Rybolovlev=E2=80=99s claims against Sotheby=
=E2=80=99s, the auction house, which he says =E2=80=9Chelped Bouvier cheat =
him, in part by creating inflated valuations for the art that served to con=
ceal Bouvier=E2=80=99s large markups.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

