   =20
      Altmaning
   =20
 =20

Usually, the founder and chief executive officer of a startup would like to=
 be able to raise money from investors while keeping complete control of th=
e company, while the investors would prefer to have some control over how t=
heir money is used. Ultimately, if there is a sharp disagreement, the inves=
tors would like to be able to=C2=A0fire=C2=A0the founder and keep the compa=
ny for themselves; the founder would like to be able to prevent that, and k=
eep the company (and their money) for herself.
This is a real tension, both sides have good reasons for their positions =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s her vision, her blood, sweat and tears;=C2=A0it=
=E2=80=99s their money =E2=80=94=C2=A0and different startups strike the bal=
ance different ways. Some startups have dual-class stock structures and sha=
reholder agreements that allow the founder to keep control of the board no =
matter how much outside money she raises. Other startups have single-class =
stock and shareholder agreements that give outside investors a lot of power=
. Generally, startups will have more founder-friendly structures if (1) the=
y are in high demand (and can thus dictate terms to investors) and (2) thei=
r founders=C2=A0care=C2=A0about this stuff; some founders are sort of innoc=
ent and say =E2=80=9Cif I focus on doing a good job the governance will wor=
k itself out,=E2=80=9D while other founders fight really hard for board con=
trol. And there are trends over time: When it is easy for startups to raise=
 money, and hard for venture capitalists to get into deals, the founders ge=
t to dictate the terms, and the venture capitalists compete over who can be=
 most founder-friendly. When capital is scarce, the providers of capital ge=
t to set the terms.
All of this is pretty straightforward stuff, a somewhat zero-sum battle bet=
ween founders and investors for control.
  [2]
=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s the investors=E2=80=99 money, it=E2=80=99s the founder=
=E2=80=99s vision, they each want protection, etc.
A weird innovation that OpenAI came up with was to introduce a=C2=A0third=
=C2=A0party that, technically,   has=C2=A0absolute control of the company, =
and can ignore=C2=A0both=C2=A0what the founder/CEO wants=C2=A0and=C2=A0what=
 the investors want. OpenAI has a board of (mostly) independent directors, =
and that board is founder/CEO Sam Altman=E2=80=99s boss and does=C2=A0not=
=C2=A0answer to the investors: It is the board of directors of a nonprofit,=
 who appoint themselves, and who have a fiduciary duty to the nonprofit=E2=
=80=99s mission of =E2=80=9Cbuilding safe and beneficial artificial general=
 intelligence for the benefit of humanity.=E2=80=9D In this structure:
=09Altman has no power over the board: He was a board member until November=
, but he had only one vote, and now the board has  kicked him off.=09The in=
vestors have no power over the board: They had no voting rights at all, and=
 OpenAI =09=09told them, in its operating agreement, that =E2=80=9Cit would=
 be wise to view any investment in OpenAI Global, LLC in the spirit of a do=
nation.=E2=80=9D

And then the board fired Altman as CEO, and Altman and the investors were b=
oth extremely upset about this and entirely aligned with each other in want=
ing him back as CEO, and in the course of a few frantic days he did in fact=
 come back as CEO. The board=E2=80=99s practical power was limited=C2=A0by =
the fact that it was neither running the company nor supplying the money:=
=C2=A0It was just some outsiders with some votes; it could neither fund the=
 development of OpenAI=E2=80=99s large language models nor, you know, do th=
at development itself. But the board=E2=80=99s=C2=A0theoretical=C2=A0power =
was total.
Anyway here=E2=80=99s a Wall Street Journal story about how, post-Open AI, =
 founders want to get more control back from investors:

The entrepreneur world was stunned to see the board of hot artificial-intel=
ligence company OpenAI fire Sam Altman just before Thanksgiving. He had bee=
n the face of one of the biggest successes of the year and suddenly he was =
out. In startup land, founders and advisers say they started discussing new=
 ways to protect themselves.
Altman eventually made it back to OpenAI in a countercoup. But the tension =
at one of the country=E2=80=99s biggest startups is playing out in a longst=
anding debate about who should control a burgeoning company. It is an inher=
ent conflict in business, with founders wanting protection for their jobs w=
hile investors want it for their money.
Among startups, tougher economic conditions have recently given venture cap=
italists and investors the upper hand. After OpenAI, founders are going to =
try to regain their footing.

Sure, fine. =E2=80=9CTougher economic conditions have recently given ventur=
e capitalists and investors the upper hand,=E2=80=9D so terms are less foun=
der-friendly, and founders would like them to be more founder-friendly, bec=
ause that is an eternal and universal tension. And =E2=80=9Cwell look at wh=
at happened to Sam Altman=E2=80=9D is, I suppose, an argument to make in th=
at negotiation.
But it has nothing to do with anything! What happened to Sam Altman is not =
that his investors disagreed with his vision and fired him! What happened t=
o Sam Altman is that OpenAI, almost uniquely, is an=20
$86 billion startup whose governance terms are=C2=A0neither=C2=A0founder-fr=
iendly=C2=A0nor investor-friendly. They are nonprofit-board-friendly. That=
=E2=80=99s so weird! If you=E2=80=99re a tech startup, you don=E2=80=99t ne=
ed a nonprofit board! The number of tech startups that answer to a nonprofi=
t board is very close to one!
  [3]
 If you don=E2=80=99t have a nonprofit board, this whole problem doesn=E2=
=80=99t exist!=C2=A0
On the other hand, if you are a founder looking to keep more control over y=
our company, there is a lot to learn from OpenAI? The Journal story discuss=
es the normal founder-friendly approaches:
Eric Ries, founder of the Long-Term Stock Exchange and something of a corpo=
rate governance guru and go-to mentor among the Silicon Valley set =E2=80=
=A6 has a system of hurdles founders can set up that would make it harder f=
or a board to move against a company=E2=80=99s mission or management. The m=
ost protective moves, Ries and lawyers say, are implementing supervoting sh=
ares or dual-class shares, which give founders ultimate control over their =
companies. These structures create multiple classes of shares to give found=
ers, and sometimes early employees or investors, voting control.
Okay sure but OpenAI has=C2=A0an operating agreement that (1) gives investo=
rs=C2=A0no votes at all=C2=A0and (2) tells them, in writing, that they shou=
ld =E2=80=9Cview any=C2=A0investment =E2=80=A6 in the spirit of a donation.=
=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s=C2=A0way=C2=A0better for a founder than dual-class=
 stock,=C2=A0if the founder is sure she controls the board.

 =20
   =20
      Carta
   =20
 =20

We  talked yesterday about Carta, the startup that manages capitalization t=
ables for other startups. I made the point that managing cap tables is a re=
asonable business =E2=80=94=C2=A0startups pay you a moderate amount of mone=
y to keep track of their shareholder lists =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is much le=
ss lucrative than the business of=C2=A0brokering secondary trades in startu=
p stock, where people will pay you, like, 2% of the value of every trade to=
 match up buyers and sellers. And managing cap tables would seem to be a hu=
ge advantage in getting the brokerage business: The lists of shareholders a=
re generally=C2=A0secret, and if you=C2=A0have them=C2=A0(because you are i=
n the business of keeping them), then you know who all the potential seller=
s are and can broker a lot of trades.
The problem is that the startups really do want those lists to be secret, a=
nd they will be mad if you go and use them to broker trades. And Carta did =
that: It came to a shareholder of a company whose cap table it manages, pit=
ching that shareholder on selling his stock; the shareholder told the compa=
ny and the company complained. And the result is that Carta is shutting dow=
n its brokerage business.=C2=A0The Financial Times reports:

The company=E2=80=99s reputation has been battered by allegations that Cart=
a staff used confidential information to solicit investors in start-ups to =
sell their stakes in the secondary market without consent from the start-up=
s themselves. ...
Henry Ward, the company=E2=80=99s chief executive, said in a blog post on M=
onday night that the lacklustre performance and ultimate closure of the tra=
ding platform was =E2=80=9Cmy greatest failure and disappointment=E2=80=9D.
=E2=80=9CBecause we have the data, if we are trading secondaries, people wi=
ll always worry that we are using the data, even if we are not. So we have =
decided to prioritise trust, and exit the secondary trading business,=E2=80=
=9D he wrote.

What I said yesterday is that =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll give you an inexpensiv=
e service and monetize it by using the data for targeted advertising=E2=80=
=9D is really=C2=A0the=C2=A0great business model of the 21st century, and t=
hat Carta=E2=80=99s service would seem to generate=C2=A0very=C2=A0valuable =
data for targeted advertising. (The advertising is =E2=80=9Csell your share=
s of this hot startup,=E2=80=9D targeted to actual shareholders.) It is rou=
gh, for a hot startup, to disavow that model. Perhaps it is a=C2=A0lesson i=
n the dangers of monetizing too early.

 =20
   =20
      Pillow talk
   =20
 =20

We   talked last June about how the Covid-19 pandemic, and the associated r=
ise in working from home, was good for work-from-home insider trading. Some=
 percentage of insider trading involves people overhearing their partners=
=E2=80=99 work calls at home, or looking at their partners=E2=80=99 work em=
ail while their partners are in the bathroom, and then trading on the partn=
ers=E2=80=99 work information. If everyone works from the office, there is =
a limited opportunity for this sort of thing. If everyone works from the be=
droom they share with their partner, there is tons of opportunity for this =
sort of thing.=C2=A0
Today there=E2=80=99s a  Wall Street Journal A-hed treatment of the trend:

There is a rich history in securities fraud of =E2=80=9Cpillow talk=E2=80=
=9D cases, in which insider traders glean confidential information from rom=
antic partners. The Covid era offered a twist: Secrets weren=E2=80=99t spil=
led in the bedroom or over a bottle of wine, but during the humdrum routine=
 of two adults working from home.
=E2=80=9CDuring Covid, there was an uptick in brazen conduct,=E2=80=9D said=
 Edward Imperatore, a defense lawyer at law firm Morrison & Foerster. =E2=
=80=9CIn a work-from-home environment, people acted with more impunity.=E2=
=80=9D
That strikes me as an obviously wrong analysis? It=E2=80=99s not that peopl=
e =E2=80=9Cacted with more impunity,=E2=80=9D that they always had access t=
o their partners=E2=80=99 inside information but became lawless monster dur=
ing Covid. It=E2=80=99s that people had way, way, way, way, way more opport=
unity=C2=A0to access their partners=E2=80=99 inside information, and the br=
azen ones made use of it.

The legal problem in these cases is: Did the insider=C2=A0tip=C2=A0her part=
ner,=C2=A0hoping=C2=A0that he would trade on her work information, or did t=
he partner=C2=A0betray=C2=A0the insider, stealing her information while she=
 wasn=E2=80=99t looking and selfishly jeopardizing her career so he could m=
ake a little money?
  [4]
=C2=A0I think the answer is usually the latter, but not always:

One challenge for prosecutors is determining whether the partner who is pri=
vy to the information was in on the crime, said former federal prosecutor B=
rendan Quigley.
=E2=80=9CDo they say, =E2=80=98Oh, my God, I would never give information t=
o my spouse or significant other?=E2=80=99 It depends not only on what actu=
ally happened, but also on the nature of their relationship,=E2=80=9D said =
Quigley, who prosecuted insider-trading cases in Manhattan.
For defense lawyers, pillow-talk cases can be difficult to handle at trial,=
 particularly if one partner testifies against another. =E2=80=9CTo a juror=
, this is the bad boyfriend,=E2=80=9D said Imperatore, the defense attorney=
. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s acting badly in a relationship in a way that goes b=
eyond the four corners of insider trading.=E2=80=9D
Not surprisingly, many such relationships don=E2=80=99t survive.

We have   talked about this problem in the case of golf buddies: Sometimes,=
 corporate executives talk about their work on the golf course, treating go=
lf like therapy and expecting their golf buddies to keep it confidential. (=
In that case, if the golf buddy trades, he is guilty of insider trading, bu=
t the executive isn=E2=80=99t.)=C2=A0Other times, corporate executives talk=
 about their work on the golf course=C2=A0in order to tip their golf buddie=
s, expecting those buddies to go trade on it. (In that case, they=E2=80=99r=
e both guilty of insider trading.)=C2=A0If you=E2=80=99re not playing the r=
ound with them, it is hard to know which cases are which. Same, but more so=
, with romantic partners.

 =20
   =20
      Shareholder Vote Exchange
   =20
 =20

We  talked last=C2=A0Thursday about the Shareholder Vote Exchange, a busine=
ss that lets retail shareholders sell their votes. My view was (1) obviousl=
y retail shareholders should sell their votes, which are worth nothing to t=
hem, but (2) who would buy them? Shareholder votes are worthless to everyon=
e, except to activist hedge funds in very rare contested proxy fights (or b=
uyers in very rare contested takeovers), and in the contested situations an=
yone who tries to buy votes is going to get very sued.
But SVE co-founder Preston Yadegar emailed me to point out the obvious use =
case I missed:=C2=A0Companies=C2=A0can buy their own shareholders=E2=80=99 =
votes. =E2=80=9COur focus for now,=E2=80=9D he writes,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cis sim=
ply to help issuers achieve quorum (with higher chances of success and at a=
 lower cost).=E2=80=9D
We have  talked a  number of  times=C2=A0in the=C2=A0last  year or two abou=
t the baroque lengths that some companies have gone to to get their retail =
shareholders to vote. Most notably, AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. was bus=
ily issuing shares to meme-stock investors, but then it ran out of authoriz=
ed shares; it wanted to ask its shareholders to authorize more shares, but =
it concluded that it couldn=E2=80=99t get enough votes, so it issued a nove=
l form of preferred stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0APES =E2=80=94=C2=A0designed to ri=
g the vote to overcome retail shareholder inertia. This led to lawsuits and=
 was generally expensive and inconvenient. I  wrote=C2=A0in 2022, about AMC=
, that =E2=80=9Cif you are a meme-stock company with a retail-focused inves=
tor-relations function, you have to solve the problem of voting.=E2=80=9D P=
ossibly the simplest solution is to pay the retail investors a few bucks fo=
r their votes.

