<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In negotiations, it is often helpful to have s=
omeone else, some =E2=80=9Cabsent principal,=E2=80=9D to blame for your pos=
ition. You go to a car dealership, the salesperson says =E2=80=9Cthis car c=
osts $25,000,=E2=80=9D you say =E2=80=9CI want to pay $21,000,=E2=80=9D she=
 says =E2=80=9CI like you, I want you in this car, but my boss won=E2=80=99=
t let me go lower than $24,000,=E2=80=9D you say =E2=80=9C$22,000,=E2=80=9D=
 she says =E2=80=9CI really want this to work out, let me check with my bos=
s,=E2=80=9D she goes into the break room and watches TikToks on her phone f=
or five minutes, she comes back and says =E2=80=9Cmy boss is really mad at =
me but I talked him down to=C2=A0$23,500.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The boss is a crutch, an excuse. The salespers=
on</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">is adversarial to you =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
she wants to charge more, you want to pay less =E2=80=94=C2=A0but</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">wants you to=C2=A0<em>feel=C2=A0</em>like s=
he=E2=80=99s on your side, so you trust her and agree to her proposals.</li=
>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way to solve the tension=C2=A0is to set up=
 some imaginary absent principal and offload all the adversarial feelings o=
nto him. =E2=80=9C<em>I=C2=A0</em>don=E2=80=99t want to charge you this muc=
h,=E2=80=9D the salesperson=C2=A0says or implies, =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s jus=
t my awful boss; really, you and I are in this together, both trying to get=
 this deal past him.=E2=80=9D And so you pay more than you wanted to, becau=
se you like her and feel like she=E2=80=99s on your side, and because she h=
as done all she can; she can=E2=80=99t get the price any lower; that=E2=80=
=99s her boss=E2=80=99s fault.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This technique is pretty shopworn at the car d=
ealership, and people have kind of=C2=A0stopped believing it, but there are=
 better versions. There are, in the world, a lot of people who are what the=
 financial industry would call =E2=80=9Cbroker-dealers=E2=80=9D:=C2=A0<em>S=
ometimes=C2=A0</em>they act as brokers, finding buyers and sellers and nego=
tiating a deal between them as pure agents, but but other times they act as=
 dealers, owning stuff for their own account and buying or selling it=C2=A0=
at whatever price they can get. Sometimes they really do have some absent p=
rincipal; other times, they are just trading for their own book.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It can be helpful, for these people, to create=
 confusion about which role they are playing. For instance if you own some =
stuff and you want to sell it for $100, and your customer says =E2=80=9CI=
=E2=80=99ll pay $80,=E2=80=9D it can be nice, for you, to say =E2=80=9Chang=
 on, let me see if the seller is willing to go down to $95.=E2=80=9D And th=
en you put the customer on hold and watch TikToks, and=C2=A0you=C2=A0come b=
ack and say =E2=80=9CI just talked to the seller, she=E2=80=99s not happy a=
nd yelled at me a lot, but I was able to talk her down to $96, but that=E2=
=80=99s the lowest she can go.=E2=80=9D And the customer appreciates your g=
ood service and your=C2=A0efforts on his behalf, and feels like you and he =
are in this together, and agrees to pay $96. But there was no seller, or ra=
ther, you were the seller, and you just didn=E2=80=99t want to go below $96=
. =E2=80=9CThe seller=E2=80=9D on the other line was just a crutch, an excu=
se. But the customer doesn=E2=80=99t know that; he thinks that you were neg=
otiating on his behalf, trying to get him the best possible deal. He doesn=
=E2=80=99t know that you were on the other side, and that you were in fact =
trying to get him the worst possible deal that he=E2=80=99d agree to.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the financial industry this is somewhere be=
tween =E2=80=9Cfrowned upon=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ca crime that you can go t=
o prison for.=E2=80=9D For a while, there was a wave of prosecutions of bon=
d traders who did this stuff; some were acquitted and some convicted, but s=
ome of the convictions were reversed and this behavior is, I don=E2=80=99t =
know, somewhat ambiguously illegal. (Obviously not legal advice!) For insta=
nce, we=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33944=
330.258408/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUt=
MDktMDgvbm9tdXJhLWJvbmQtdHJhZGVycy1ib3VnaHQtbG93LWFuZC1zb2xkLWhpZ2g_Y21waWQ=
9QkJEMDEwOTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZX=
R0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMTA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB8cad323f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">once talked about</a> a US Securities and Exchan=
ge Commission case against some Nomura traders who allegedly=C2=A0did stuff=
 like this<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On March 18, 2011, Peters learned =
that Nomura had purchased a block of the bond JPMMT 2006-A3 2A1 at 71-08. S=
hortly thereafter, Peters contacted a representative of a Nomura customer (=
=E2=80=9CCustomer E=E2=80=9D) and falsely claimed that the bond was being o=
ffered at 75-24, implying that a third-party, and not Nomura, owned the bon=
d. Peters then elaborated on the misrepresentation, saying that the =E2=80=
=9Cseller=E2=80=9D (who did not exist) probably had =E2=80=9Ca little room=
=E2=80=9D (meaning, to lower the price) but that the bond=E2=80=99s price l=
ikely would not fall by more than a point. The Customer E representative di=
rected Peters to =E2=80=9CFOK=E2=80=9D (short for =E2=80=9Cfill or kill,=E2=
=80=9D which is industry jargon for =E2=80=9Clast and final offer=E2=80=9D)=
 at 74-24, to which Peters replied, =E2=80=9CFOK worked!=E2=80=9D By mislea=
ding the Customer E representative about the fictional [offer] from the pha=
ntom seller, Peters extracted over $117,000 in additional profits for Nomur=
a.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Customer E there thinks that Peters is doing a=
 good job on his behalf, advising the customer on negotiating=C2=A0with the=
 seller and talking the seller down to the lowest possible price. But in fa=
ct Peters is doing a good job on his=C2=A0<em>own=C2=A0</em>behalf, getting=
 the customer to pay the highest possible price (to Peters) by=C2=A0<em>pre=
tending=C2=A0</em>there is some absent seller on the other side.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This trade was for somewhat thinly traded resi=
dential mortgage-backed securities, by the way, which is important.=C2=A0On=
e reason that this trick doesn=E2=80=99t work that well anymore at car deal=
erships, and that it doesn=E2=80=99t work at all in=C2=A0the stock market, =
is that you need a customer who has no idea what the underlying thing is ac=
tually worth. You can=E2=80=99t go around pretending to negotiate the price=
 of a share of Apple Inc. stock, because the customer can just look on a sc=
reen and see its price, accurate to the penny and the second. You=C2=A0<em>=
could </em>go around pretending to negotiate the price of a Honda, but the =
internet has made=C2=A0car prices more transparent than they used to be. Li=
ttle stubs of weird RMBS trade by appointment, and Nomura plausibly does ha=
ve a much better idea what they cost than its customers do, so it can push =
up the price by doing a weird little pantomime negotiation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile in the art market prices are more or=
 less entirely imaginary; a Gustav Klimt painting is worth, to a billionair=
e art collector, roughly $1 more than one other billionaire is willing to p=
ay for it. So if you just make up a guy who thinks it=E2=80=99s worth $185 =
million, maybe you can get your real billionaire customer to pay that much.=
 The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33944330.2584=
08/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyNC8wMS8wNC9hcnRzL2Rlc2lnbi9kbWl0cnkt=
cnlib2xvdmxldi1zb3RoZWJ5cy10cmlhbC5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB25500596"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> New York Times reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For example, in 2012, Bouvier told Rybolovlev=
=E2=80=99s aide that the sellers of a Klimt, =E2=80=9CWater Serpents II,=E2=
=80=9D were looking for $190 million, but that he thought he could =E2=80=
=9Ctwist them to get 185,=E2=80=9D according to court papers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThese negotiations did not happen,=E2=
=80=9D Judge Furman wrote in his March opinion.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the same day in 2012 that Bouvier wrote tha=
t email, one of his companies bought the painting for $126 million. Two day=
s later, he invoiced Rybolovlev for $183.8 million.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bouvier is Yves Bouvier, an art broker-dealer,=
 and Rybolovlev is Dmitry Rybolovlev, =E2=80=9Ca Russian oligarch=E2=80=9D =
and collector. Bouvier would sometimes buy art for his own account and then=
 sell it to=C2=A0Rybolovlev at markups of tens of millions of dollars, whic=
h is a good trade if he=E2=80=99s a dealer and bad work if he=E2=80=99s a b=
roker. The dispute is about which he was:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For years, Rybolovlev has accused Bouvier of d=
efrauding him in that and dozens of other transactions by posing as an art =
adviser negotiating sales on Rybolovlev=E2=80=99s behalf, when, in fact, he=
 was secretly acting as an art dealer and often increasing the prices by te=
ns of millions of dollars. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bouvier has long insisted he was always clear =
that he was operating not solely as an adviser, but also as an independent =
dealer. As evidence, he has put forward sales contracts for Rybolovlev=E2=
=80=99s first few purchases as proof he was openly operating as a dealer, f=
ree to charge whatever price Rybolovlev was prepared to pay.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the Russian collector has said that Bouvie=
r=E2=80=99s role evolved into that of commissioned adviser and agent, and t=
hat Bouvier pretended to play that role. He has emails in which Bouvier des=
cribed negotiations with sellers that do not appear to have actually taken =
place.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have talked about this case <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33944330.258408/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMTEtMTcvYWJzZW50LXJlZ3VsYXRv=
cnMtYW5kLWFjdGl2aXN0LXZvdGVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMDkyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWR=
pdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDEwOSZ1dG1fY2FtcG=
FpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7b96be61" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> before</a>=
, over the years; Rybolovlev has been pursuing Bouvier =E2=80=9Cin jurisdic=
tions that included Monaco, Singapore, Hong Kong and Geneva,=E2=80=9D but h=
as mostly lost. This week in New York there will be a trial on=C2=A0Rybolov=
lev=E2=80=99s claims against Sotheby=E2=80=99s, the auction house, which he=
 says =E2=80=9Chelped Bouvier cheat him, in part by creating inflated valua=
tions for the art that served to conceal Bouvier=E2=80=99s large markups.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
