<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then the board fired Altman as CEO, and Al=
tman and the investors were both extremely upset about this and entirely al=
igned with each other in wanting him back as CEO, and in the course of a fe=
w frantic days he did in fact come back as CEO. The board=E2=80=99s practic=
al power was limited=C2=A0<em>by the fact that it was neither running the c=
ompany nor supplying the money:=C2=A0</em>It was just some outsiders with s=
ome votes; it could neither fund the development of OpenAI=E2=80=99s large =
language models nor, you know, do that development itself. But the board=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0<em>theoretical=C2=A0</em>power was total.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here=E2=80=99s a Wall Street Journal st=
ory about how, post-Open AI, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/33944330.258408/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9idXNpbmVzcy9lbnRyZXBy=
ZW5ldXJzaGlwL3N0YXJ0dXAtZm91bmRlcnMtZnJldC1vdmVyLWdldHRpbmctZmlyZWQtbGlrZS1=
